{
  "text": "Epigenomic profiling of adenomas from Apc Min/+ mice has also been useful in the identification of patient relevant, early disease biomarkers (Fig. 2) . Immunoprecipitation of methylated DNA followed by sequencing (known as 'MeDIP-seq') identified regions of the genome were differentially methylated [CITATION_1] . These regions were mainly enriched for targets of the Polycomb Repressive Complex, the subunits of which, together with those for several DNA methyltransferase complexes, were up-regulated in adenomas. This genomewide pattern was shown to be partly conserved in human colon carcinomas, suggesting that an epigenetic signature is established early and is retained during progression from adenoma to carcinoma.",
  "correct_citation": {
    "[CITATION_1]": "13993370"
